column2:
The following statistics have been produced by Dr Ben Smith (Research Associate in Hydrology - Ben.Smith4@ncl.ac.uk | Newcastle University | School of Engineering | Water Group) as a follow on project from the OpenCLIM project, seeking to inform MPs of the increase hydrological risk in their constituencies from climate change. All results are modelled using a hydrological model (SHETRAN) and given as a median of the 12 RCMs. They therefore do not portray extremes well, but are easier to communicate. Data is given as change between the 30 year period over which 2 degrees of warming is reached (approximately 2015-2045 in the UKCP18 12km datasets, differeing by a few years depending on which RCM is used) and a baseline period of 1985-2010. All counts have been normalised to account for the 5yr difference in period length (due to the first 5 years being requiredfor model spinup). Rainfall uplifts were taken from https://artefacts.ceda.ac.uk/badc_datadocs/future-drainage/FUTURE_DRAINAGE_Guidance_for_applying_rainfall_uplifts.pdf

One thing of note is that high flows are shown to decrease in some catchments - this poses the risk of displaying false negatives (perhaps leading to inaction), rather than false positives (where action is taken but unneeded if stats incorrectly indicate flood increase). In these instances it may be important to note that some RCMs do indicate increases in flood flows. Furthermore, as these are daily flows, the sub daily flows, from storm rainfall, could still increase flows on a subdaily timeframe.
